'''Richard J. "Spike" Carey''' (January 7, 1929 - July 19, 2013) was an American politician from [[Maine]].<ref name="Spike Carey">{{cite news|url=http://www.onlinesentinel.com/news/Spike-Carey-longtime-legislator-Waterville-and-Belgrade-politician-dies.html|title='Spike' Carey, longtime legislator, Waterville and Belgrade politician, dies|coauthors=STAFF REPORT|date=July 22, 2013|work=[[Morning Sentinel]]|accessdate=22 July 2013}}</ref> Carey served as the [[List of mayors of Waterville, Maine|Mayor of Waterville, Maine]] from 1970 to 1978. From 1967 to 1978, Carey also represented [[Waterville, Maine|Waterville]] in the [[Maine House of Representatives]]. He served in the [[Maine Senate]] from 1992 to 2000. After leaving the He ran again for State Senate in 2004 against incumbent [[Chandler Woodcock]] and lost.

==Personal==
Carey was born and raised in the French-speaking South End of Waterville and did not speak English until he was 12 years old. His father was a member of the Waterville City Council. He graduated from [[Waterville High School]].<ref name="Richard">{{cite web|url=http://digilib.bates.edu/cgi-bin/library.cgi?e=d-01000-00---off-0muskieor--00-1----0-10-0---0---0direct-10---4-------0-0l--11-it-50---20-help---01-3-1-00-0-0-11-1-0gbk-00&a=d&c=muskieor&cl=CL3.3&d=HASH58347f191c2a5d88693562|title=Interview with Richard 'Spike' Carey|last=Richard|first=Mike|date=August 26, 1999|publisher=[[Bates College]]|accessdate=22 July 2013|location=Belgrade, Maine}}</ref>

